"""
MKT Context Commentary — John chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-john-19-21.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/john.json (chs 1–13 for continuity)
- data/commentary/ellicott/john.json (philological background)
- data/commentary/jfb/john.json (historical background)

Key decisions in this range:
- "The Evangelist" maintained throughout
- "The Jewish leaders" / "the chief priests" for hoi Ioudaioi in juridical contexts
- Pilate's political situation (Sejanus, amicus Caesaris) treated as historically relevant context
- 14 Nisan timing: Johannine chronology (crucifixion on day lambs are slaughtered)
  treated as deliberate theological framing, not merely as conflicting with Synoptics
- The anthrakia (charcoal fire) at 21:9 treated as a deliberate verbal echo of 18:18
  — the Evangelist signals Peter's restoration by repeating the exact setting of his denial
- agapas/phileis distinction at 21:15-17: noted as potentially meaningful but treated
  with appropriate caution — the Evangelist often varies synonyms without sharp distinction
- The Beloved Disciple's identity left appropriately open — "the Evangelist" used for
  the author throughout; "the Beloved Disciple" as the character within the narrative
- 153 fish: Jerome's species-count interpretation noted as ancient; numerical symbolism
  treated as possible but not asserted as the Evangelist's intent
- Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus's spices: royal burial quantity flagged; the
  Nicodemus connection to 7:50-51 noted as completing a character arc
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


JOHN = {
  "19": {
    "1": '<p>Roman flogging (<em>flagellatio</em>) was administered with a leather whip strung with lead pellets or bone fragments — the <em>flagellum</em>. It could be applied as a preliminary to crucifixion or as a standalone punishment. Pilate may have offered it here as a compromise: a severe but technically non-capital sentence that might satisfy the crowd\'s demand for visible punishment. The Evangelist presents it as one stage in the trial rather than the final sentence, underscoring that the escalation to crucifixion required further pressure.</p>',

    "2": '<p>The mock coronation by the soldiers was a parody of Roman imperial acclamation ritual. The purple robe mimicked the distinctive color worn exclusively by Roman emperors (Tyrian purple, derived from murex mollusks, was so expensive that only imperial households could legally wear it). The crown of thorns, a reed scepter (implied by the Synoptic accounts), and the ritual salutation "Hail, King of the Jews" directly mirror "Ave, Caesar" — the soldiers were staging a grotesque investiture ceremony, substituting a Judean prisoner for the emperor. The scene was entertaining to soldiers who presided over provincial pretensions; for the Evangelist it drips with irony, since the mockery accidentally enacts the truth.</p>',

    "3": '<p>"Hail, king of the Jews!" is a deliberate echo of the imperial salute <em>Ave, Caesar</em> and of the legionary acclamation by which emperors were proclaimed. Coming from soldiers, it was ridicule; coming from the Evangelist\'s vantage point, it is inadvertent proclamation. The slapping (<em>edidoun autō rapismata</em>) was a gesture of contempt in the ancient world — it communicated that the recipient was beneath the dignity of a proper blow; slaves and social inferiors were slapped, not struck as equals.</p>',

    "4": '<p>Pilate\'s repeated declarations of Jesus\'s innocence ("I find no basis for a charge against him" — three times in this Gospel: 18:38; 19:4; 19:6) follow the Roman legal pattern of formal acquittal statements (<em>absolvo</em>) by a magistrate. In Roman law, if a judge declared the accused innocent, the prosecution had to provide stronger grounds to continue. Pilate is going through the motions of a legal proceeding while being pressured outside normal judicial channels. The irony of a Roman magistrate insisting on the innocence of a man he is about to execute is the Evangelist\'s pointed commentary on the justice system of the empire.</p>',

    "5": '<p>"Here is the man" (<em>Idou ho anthrōpos</em>) was Pilate\'s attempt at the politics of pity: presenting a figure already beaten, humiliated, and crowned with thorns, he hoped the sight would satisfy the demand for punishment without requiring execution. In Roman judicial practice this kind of display — the <em>ostentatio</em> of a sufficiently chastened prisoner — was a recognized strategy for de-escalating crowd pressure. The Evangelist\'s Greek phrase also resonates with Zechariah\'s messianic figure called "the Man" (<em>Ish</em>, Zech 6:12 LXX: <em>Anatolē onoma autō</em>), though whether the Evangelist intends this echo is debated.</p>',

    "6": '<p>The demand to crucify carried specific social force. Crucifixion was the punishment reserved for slaves, rebels, pirates, and non-citizens; it was considered the most shameful death in the Roman world. A Roman orator could describe it as a death "too shameful to describe" (<em>summum supplicium</em>, Cicero, <em>In Verrem</em> 2.5.165). That the Jewish leaders were demanding crucifixion rather than stoning (their normal capital method under Jewish law) was itself a social maneuver: it put the execution in Roman hands and avoided the risk of the crowd (or the disciples) seizing the body for veneration as a martyr. Pilate\'s response — "You take him and crucify him" — is a calculated deflection; he knows they lack legal authority to carry out a Roman execution.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The appeal to "our law" shifts the charge from political sedition (king of the Jews) to blasphemy under Levitical law. Leviticus 24:16 prescribed death for blasphemy: "Anyone who blasphemes the name of the LORD is to be put to death." The specific charge — that Jesus "claimed to be the Son of God" — is the blasphemy the Sanhedrin had determined warranted death (18:19–24; cf. Mark 14:61–64). In Jewish theological framework, "Son of God" was a claim to a unique divine identity that no human being could legitimately make; the charge is that Jesus has violated the boundary between creator and creature. The leaders are now offering Pilate a legal basis under Jewish law that he, as a Roman, could accommodate — or dismiss.</p>',

    "8": '<p>Pilate\'s "even more afraid" (<em>mallon ephobēthē</em>) is usually read through the lens of Roman piety about divine beings. Romans were not monotheists and were not immune to concern about offending a god traveling incognito — the literary motif of gods disguised as humans who punish those who mistreat them was well established (Homer\'s <em>Odyssey</em>; Ovid\'s <em>Metamorphoses</em>). The title "Son of God" in Roman culture could mean an emperor (Augustus was <em>divi filius</em>, son of the deified Julius) or a divine figure with supernatural origins. Pilate\'s new unease may be a mixture of Roman superstition and growing discomfort with the dynamics of the trial.</p>',

    "9": '<p>Pilate\'s question "Where do you come from?" has a double register that the Evangelist has been exploiting throughout the Gospel: the surface question is about geographical origin (Galilee? Judea?), but the deeper question — Jesus\'s heavenly origin — has been the Gospel\'s central claim since the prologue. Jesus\'s silence here echoes Isaiah\'s Servant who "did not open his mouth" before his shearers (Isa 53:7). In Roman judicial practice, a defendant\'s silence could be legally prejudicial; Jesus\'s silence is presented not as inability to respond but as chosen restraint.</p>',

    "10": '<p>Pilate invokes his <em>imperium</em> — the absolute authority of a Roman magistrate over life and death within his jurisdiction. The technical term <em>ius gladii</em> (the right of the sword) designated the governor\'s authority to execute without appeal. Pilate\'s rhetorical question assumes this power is self-evidently supreme. The Johannine irony is that the man asserting absolute temporal authority is the one who is actually being maneuvered by the crowd, while the silent prisoner holds the genuinely authoritative position.</p>',

    "11": '<p>Jesus\'s response that authority comes "from above" (<em>anōthen</em>) uses the same word as 3:3 ("born again/from above"), activating its double meaning. The claim is not merely that God permits human authority to exist (a standard Jewish and Stoic political theology) but that this specific authority over this specific trial has a specific divine purpose. The comparative guilt — "the one who delivered me to you has the greater sin" — likely refers to Caiaphas (the one who formally handed Jesus over, 18:28–30) rather than Judas, though both are in view. Jewish legal thinking did distinguish degrees of culpability based on the degree of intention and the position of authority: a judge who condemns unjustly bears more guilt than the executioner who acts under orders.</p>',

    "12": '<p>"Friend of Caesar" (<em>philos tou Kaisaros</em>, <em>amicus Caesaris</em>) was a formal honorary title in the Roman client network. To be named an <em>amicus Caesaris</em> was to enjoy imperial patronage and protection; to lose it was political ruin. Pilate had been appointed prefect of Judea under the patronage of Lucius Aelius Sejanus (Tiberius\'s powerful prefect of the Praetorian Guard), who was also known for anti-Jewish policies. Sejanus was executed in 31 CE; after his fall, Tiberius expected provincial governors to maintain order without provoking the populations they governed. Pilate, operating in this post-Sejanus environment, was politically vulnerable: a complaint to Rome that he had released a man claiming to be a king would paint him as soft on sedition. The crowd\'s threat activates precisely this vulnerability.</p>',

    "13": '<p>The <em>bēma</em> (judgment seat) was the raised stone or marble platform from which Roman magistrates delivered official judgments — physically elevated to signal the magistrate\'s authority over those below. <em>Lithostroton</em> (Greek, "paved with stone") and <em>Gabbatha</em> (Aramaic, "raised place" or "ridge") describe the same location from different linguistic perspectives: the Evangelist gives both names, as he does for other dual-language sites (Golgotha, 19:17; Siloam, 9:7). Archaeological excavations have uncovered paved stone areas near the Antonia Fortress and near Herod\'s palace — both proposed as candidates for the site — but the identification remains uncertain.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The phrase "day of Preparation of the Passover" (<em>paraskeuē tou pascha</em>) places the crucifixion on 14 Nisan — the day when Passover lambs were slaughtered in the Temple (afternoon), not the day after the Passover meal. This is John\'s chronology, which differs from the Synoptic chronology where the Last Supper is the Passover meal (making the crucifixion 15 Nisan). The Evangelist\'s timing aligns the death of Jesus with the slaughter of the Passover lambs: at approximately noon ("the sixth hour"), when Pilate presents Jesus for judgment, the Temple priests begin preparing to slaughter the lambs. Whether this is a deliberate theological alignment or an independent historical tradition (or both) is debated; the Evangelist\'s consistent Passover-lamb imagery (1:29, 19:36) makes it likely that the timing is theologically loaded.</p>',

    "15": '<p>"We have no king but Caesar" is an extraordinary statement from the chief priests, who would normally resist any affirmation of Roman sovereignty as religiously and politically compromising. For first-century Jews, the fundamental claim was that God alone was Israel\'s true king (1 Sam 8:7; Ps 149:2); acknowledging Caesar as the only legitimate king was a theological capitulation. The Evangelist frames this as the ultimate irony of the trial: in their determination to destroy Jesus, the guardians of Jewish covenantal identity publicly disavow the covenantal claim that God is Israel\'s king. It is simultaneously a politically calculated statement and a theologically self-damning one.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The handover is legally complex: Pilate, having formally found Jesus innocent three times, now hands him over to execution. Roman law technically required the magistrate to pronounce the death sentence formally; the Evangelist\'s account of the handover implies this without quoting it verbatim. The phrase "the soldiers took charge of Jesus" confirms that a Roman military unit, not the Jewish leaders, carried out the crucifixion — a Roman execution for a Roman sentence, whatever the political pressure that produced it.</p>',

    "17": '<p>The condemned typically carried the horizontal beam of the cross (<em>patibulum</em>) to the execution site, where the vertical post (<em>stipes</em>) was already installed. The Synoptic accounts record Simon of Cyrene being pressed into service at some point on the route (Mark 15:21); the Evangelist omits this detail, presenting Jesus as bearing his own cross throughout — a detail that has been read both as historical and as Christological emphasis (the king carries his own cross to his throne). Golgotha ("Place of the Skull," <em>kranion</em> in Greek, <em>Calvaria</em> in Latin) was an execution site near the city wall: far enough outside for legal purposes (crucifixion was performed outside the city per Jewish law) but close enough to be visible as a deterrent.</p>',

    "18": '<p>Crucifixion with "two others" on either side places Jesus at the center — a position of either special dishonor or (in the Evangelist\'s ironic reading) enthroned primacy. The "two others" are identified in the Synoptics as <em>lēstai</em> (brigands, rebels, or highway robbers) — a term also applied to the Barabbas who was released in Jesus\'s place (18:40). The association of Jesus with those convicted of violent crime or insurrection fulfills Isaiah\'s description of the Servant: "he was numbered with the transgressors" (Isa 53:12), a passage the Synoptics explicitly cite (Luke 22:37) though the Evangelist does not quote it here.</p>',

    "19": '<p>The <em>titulus</em> was a placard (usually a whitened wooden board) announcing the charge against a condemned person; it was either carried before him in the procession or attached to the cross. The trilingual inscription — Hebrew (or Aramaic), Latin, and Greek — corresponded to the three languages of authority in Roman Palestine: Hebrew/Aramaic (the language of the Jewish people and Scripture), Latin (the language of Roman administration and law), and Greek (the commercial and intellectual language of the eastern Empire). The trilingual proclamation of Jesus\'s identity as "King of the Jews" in all three registers is, for the Evangelist, an inadvertent universal proclamation of his kingship across every sphere of the ancient world.</p>',

    "20": '<p>The note that "many of the Jews read this sign" emphasizes the public, witnessed character of both the crucifixion and its charge. Jerusalem during Passover was crowded with pilgrims — estimates range from hundreds of thousands to over a million — and the site near the city wall ensured maximum visibility. The trilingual inscription meant literacy was not required for any of the three major language communities to grasp the charge. The Evangelist\'s attention to the wide readership of the title sets up the confrontation that follows: the inscription was not a private administrative detail but a public declaration.</p>',

    "21": '<p>The chief priests\' objection to the wording reveals the political stakes of the inscription. "The King of the Jews" was Pilate\'s sentence: it identified Jesus as a person Rome had determined was a threat to order and executed as such. The leaders wanted it reworded as the man\'s own claim ("that man said, I am King of the Jews") — a subtle but important difference: the current inscription reads as if Pilate acknowledged the title as accurate, while the proposed revision frames it as a delusional self-claim. The distinction matters for how the execution would be read by the Passover crowd.</p>',

    "22": '<p>Pilate\'s response "What I have written, I have written" (<em>ho gegrapha, gegrapha</em>) is a formula of Roman administrative finality. Once an official judgment was inscribed and publicly posted, Roman legal practice did not permit alteration; the magistrate\'s written word had the force of law. Pilate\'s stubbornness here may reflect genuine irritation (the crowd had already maneuvered him into an execution he did not want), or it may be a moment of deliberate assertion of Roman authority over against Jewish pressure. The Evangelist almost certainly reads it as something else: the sovereign word stands, and no human authority can revise what God has inscribed over the cross.</p>',

    "23": '<p>Roman soldiers were entitled to the clothing of condemned prisoners as a perquisite of their duty — one of the practical compensations for an unpleasant task. A four-man execution squad (<em>quaternio</em>) was standard for Roman crucifixion. The division of garments into four shares, one per soldier, was straightforward; the tunic presented a problem because it was woven seamlessly in one piece. The seamless tunic (<em>chitōn</em> without seam, <em>arraphos</em>) was a distinctive garment; Josephus (<em>Ant.</em> 3.7.4) notes that the high priest\'s inner tunic was similarly seamless and woven in one piece. Whether the Evangelist intends a typological connection to the high-priestly garment is debated, but the detail is emphasized enough that readers are meant to notice it.</p>',

    "24": '<p>The soldiers\' decision to cast lots rather than tear the tunic fulfills Psalm 22:18: "They divide my clothes among them and cast lots for my garment." Psalm 22 begins with the cry of dereliction ("My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?") and moves through a description of suffering that corresponds with striking detail to crucifixion — pierced hands and feet (v.16), bones out of joint (v.14), surrounded by enemies (v.13), exposed and humiliated — before ending in vindication and universal praise. The Evangelist quotes only the garment-casting verse, but readers familiar with the whole psalm would hear it as an activation of the full Psalm 22 register of suffering and vindication.</p>',

    "25": '<p>Jewish women were expected to be present at burials and to lead the mourning — this was both a social obligation and a cultural honor. In contrast to the Synoptic accounts, which place the women "at a distance," the Evangelist places them "near the cross" (<em>para tō staurō</em>), a detail that may reflect independent tradition or theological emphasis. The identification of the women presents difficulties: "his mother\'s sister" and "Mary the wife of Clopas" may be two people or one (with "his mother\'s sister" standing in apposition to "Mary wife of Clopas"), which affects whether the two Marys are related. The Beloved Disciple is also present — the only male disciple named at the cross.</p>',

    "26": '<p>The address "Woman" (<em>gynai</em>) is not disrespectful in Greek — it is the standard vocative for an adult woman, used as an address to a queen or a goddess as well as to ordinary women. Jesus uses the same address to Mary at Cana (2:4) and to the Samaritan woman (4:21). The commendation of Mary to the Beloved Disciple\'s care creates a new kinship bond in place of the natural one — "here is your son" and "here is your mother" are adoption formulae that constitute a legal and social relationship. In a world where a widow without sons had no social security, the arrangement was practically significant; theologically, the Beloved Disciple represents the ideal disciple who remains faithful when others have scattered.</p>',

    "27": '<p>The phrase "from that hour the disciple took her into his own home" (<em>eis ta idia</em>) uses the same phrase as 1:11 ("his own did not receive him"). The Evangelist has been tracking the <em>idia</em>/<em>idios</em> (own/one\'s own) language throughout: now a disciple who remained receives the mother of the one the world rejected. The domestic arrangement was not metaphorical: in the ancient world, a widowed woman with no surviving male household member depended entirely on the charity or obligation of others; the Beloved Disciple\'s acceptance of this responsibility is a material act of discipleship.</p>',

    "28": '<p>"Knowing that everything had now been finished" (<em>panta ēdē tetelestai</em>) presents Jesus as fully in control of the timing of his death — he does not die from loss of control but acts with knowledge of completion. The phrase "so that Scripture would be fulfilled" before "I thirst" suggests the Evangelist sees the declaration itself as a fulfillment act; the most likely texts in view are Psalm 22:15 ("my mouth is dried up like a potsherd") and Psalm 69:21 ("they put gall in my food and gave me vinegar for my thirst"). The Evangelist patterns the death sequence as a series of deliberate fulfillments rather than an involuntary sequence of suffering.</p>',

    "29": '<p><em>Oxos</em> (sour wine, vinegar) was the soldiers\' standard field ration — the Roman military issued <em>posca</em>, a mixture of water and sour wine, as a practical drink for duty. A jar of it at an execution site was unremarkable. The hyssop branch used to lift the sponge is the theologically loaded detail: Exodus 12:22 instructs Israel to use a bunch of hyssop to apply the Passover lamb\'s blood to the doorposts. In both cases, hyssop is the instrument by which the sacrifice\'s fluid reaches its destination — in the Exodus, blood on the doorpost; here, sour wine to the lips of the one the Evangelist has identified as the Passover lamb. Whether the Evangelist intends the echo (given the chronological alignment of John 19:14) or whether hyssop was simply what was at hand is debated; the Evangelist typically places such details without commentary.</p>',

    "30": '<p><em>Tetelestai</em> ("It is finished") appears in commercial papyri from Egypt as the standard notation stamped on receipts and accounts to indicate full payment — "paid in full." The word is the perfect passive of <em>teleō</em> (to complete, discharge a debt, bring to an end). In the commercial context it communicated that an obligation had been fully satisfied and no residual claim remained. Jesus\'s bowing of his head and "handing over the spirit" (<em>paredōken to pneuma</em>) uses a more active verb than the standard "he died" or "he breathed his last" of the Synoptics — the Greek implies a deliberate act of surrender rather than passive expiration, consistent with the Evangelist\'s portrait of Jesus as directing events to their end rather than being swept along by them.</p>',

    "31": '<p>Jewish law derived from Deuteronomy 21:22–23 required that a hanged person\'s body not remain on the tree overnight ("you must not leave the body hanging on the pole overnight. Be sure to bury it that same day, because anyone who is hung on a pole is under God\'s curse"). The Passover Sabbath created a doubled urgency: it was both a weekly Sabbath and one of the major festival days, making it a "great/special Sabbath" (<em>megalē</em> in the Evangelist\'s phrase). The procedure requested — <em>crurifragium</em>, the breaking of the legs — hastened death by eliminating the condemned person\'s ability to push up on the footrest to breathe; without that leverage, asphyxiation followed quickly. It was a standard Roman procedure for expediting execution when time was a factor.</p>',

    "32": '<p>The breaking of the legs of the two men crucified with Jesus is presented straightforwardly: the soldiers began with the two men on either side, working outward from Jesus or from one end to the other. That they needed to break the legs of these two men (they were still alive) while finding Jesus already dead reverses the expected order of endurance. Crucifixion could take days; death within hours was unusually rapid, which is why the Synoptic account records Pilate\'s surprise that Jesus was already dead (Mark 15:44).</p>',

    "33": '<p>The soldiers\' confirmation that Jesus was already dead served the Roman practical and legal purpose of certifying the execution was complete before allowing the body to be released. Roman military practice required that officers ensure condemned persons were actually dead; premature release of a living condemned person would have constituted dereliction of duty. The detail also functions apologetically in the Evangelist\'s narrative: the physical examination by trained military personnel rules out the possibility that Jesus had merely lost consciousness and revived later — a rationalist explanation that would appear in later centuries.</p>',

    "34": '<p>The spear thrust to the side (<em>eis tēn pleuran autou enuxen</em>) confirmed death and simultaneously produced the flow of "blood and water." Medical interpretations propose that this reflects post-mortem separation of blood cells and serum (a real phenomenon when a corpse has been in position for some time), or rupture of the pericardial sac producing the two fluids separately. The Evangelist\'s emphasis on the detail — he inserts an unusual eyewitness claim at v.35 specifically to validate this — suggests it carried theological freight. Early interpretation connected the two fluids to baptism and the Eucharist; Augustine and others developed this reading. Whether or not the Evangelist intends a sacramental allegory, the detail was clearly not incidental to him.</p>',

    "35": '<p>The eyewitness claim here ("The man who saw it has given testimony, and his testimony is true") is unique in the Fourth Gospel and is formally constructed: it uses the third person about the Beloved Disciple (who is presumably the "he" of the verse), then explicitly invites the reader\'s belief. The construction "he knows that he tells the truth" is a legally weighted formula — in Greek evidentiary procedure, a witness could testify to what he himself had seen and then attest that his testimony was true. The Evangelist\'s insertion of this testimony clause at precisely this point (the blood and water from the side) signals that this detail is crucial enough to require eyewitness warrant, not just narrative report.</p>',

    "36": '<p>The fulfilled Scripture "Not one of his bones will be broken" (<em>ostoun ou suntribēsetai autou</em>) most immediately echoes Exodus 12:46 and Numbers 9:12, which specify that no bone of the Passover lamb shall be broken — instructions that presupposed the lamb was to be roasted whole. Psalm 34:20 ("He protects all his bones; not one of them will be broken") is also in view, applying to the righteous sufferer under God\'s protection. The Evangelist sees both texts as converging at the cross: Jesus is simultaneously the Passover lamb whose structural integrity is preserved and the righteous sufferer whom God protects even in death.</p>',

    "37": '<p>The second fulfilled Scripture — "They will look on the one they have pierced" — comes from Zechariah 12:10. The LXX translates this verse differently from the Hebrew: the LXX reads "they shall look upon me because they have mocked" (or "danced over") rather than "they will look on the one they have pierced." The Evangelist\'s quotation follows the Hebrew (<em>wehibbîṭû ʾēlāyw ʾēt ʾāšer-dāqārû</em>) more closely, suggesting direct access to the Hebrew text or a different Greek translation. Zechariah 12:10 has the unusual feature of the speaker switching from "the LORD" to "me" — a grammatical shift that made the verse significant in early Christian readings of the divine nature of the one pierced. Revelation 1:7 also cites this verse as a future event; John 19:37 presents its beginning-fulfillment at the cross.</p>',

    "38": '<p>Joseph of Arimathea is identified by all four Gospels as a member of the Sanhedrin and a "secret disciple" who had not consented to the council\'s decision (Luke 23:51). Arimathea is most likely <em>Harimathayim</em> (1 Sam 1:1, home of Samuel\'s father Elkanah), a Judean town. His request to Pilate for the body of Jesus follows standard Roman procedure: a family member or recognized patron of the deceased could petition the governor for the release of a body for proper burial. Roman law allowed governors to release crucifixion victims for burial at their discretion (they were not required to do so, and could deny it for enemies of the state). That a member of the Sanhedrin made the request — and was granted it — suggests the council had achieved what it wanted with the execution and was prepared to permit burial.</p>',

    "39": '<p>Nicodemus reappears here for the first time since 7:50–51, where he had offered a mild procedural defense of Jesus before the Pharisees ("Does our law condemn a man without first hearing him?"). His coming in secret at night in chapter 3 — the Evangelist uses the same <em>nyktos</em> (night) here — has now given way to public action: he comes openly to assist in the burial, with an enormous quantity of aromatic spices. The mixture of myrrh and aloes (approximately 100 Roman <em>litrai</em> — 65–75 modern pounds) was a royal burial quantity. Josephus records that five hundred slaves carrying spices accompanied Herod the Great\'s funeral procession (<em>Ant.</em> 17.8.3); the quantity Nicodemus brings places the burial of Jesus at a level of honor normally reserved for royalty or heads of state. The secret seeker of chapter 3 has become a public witness at the tomb.</p>',

    "40": '<p>The note that wrapping the body with spices "was in accordance with Jewish burial customs" (<em>ethos tōn Ioudaiōn</em>) signals the Evangelist\'s awareness that his readership includes people unfamiliar with Jewish practice. Jewish burial custom involved preparing the body as soon as possible after death, wrapping it in linen strips with aromatic preparations applied between the layers. Embalming in the Egyptian sense (removal of organs and preservation of the body) was not practiced; the spices masked decomposition and honored the dead. The linen strips (<em>othonia</em>) would later be found lying in the tomb by Peter and the Beloved Disciple (20:5–6) — their careful arrangement argues against the tomb having been disturbed by grave robbers.</p>',

    "41": '<p>The garden setting is noted specifically and is theologically resonant in the Evangelist\'s framework. The Fourth Gospel\'s passion begins in a garden (18:1) and ends in a garden — an echo-structure the Evangelist uses to bracket the events. A new tomb "in which no one had ever been laid" fulfills practical requirements (no previous occupant whose burial rites might conflict with the urgent timing) but also signals the absence of any prior human claim on the space where resurrection will occur. "New tomb" carries the same theological weight as "new commandment" (13:34) and the "new birth" of chapter 3: in the Evangelist\'s vocabulary, <em>kainos</em> (new in quality) marks the irruption of God\'s transforming action.</p>',

    "42": '<p>The proximity of the tomb to the execution site meant the burial could be completed before the Sabbath began at sunset — under an hour away at the "sixth hour" (noon, 19:14), though the actual crucifixion to death to burial sequence compressed into an afternoon. The urgency of the Preparation day burial contrasts with the royal extravagance of the spices: Joseph and Nicodemus acted with both haste and lavishness. Jewish law required that burial take place before sunset, and the Passover Sabbath added additional urgency; the haste means the burial was incomplete (the women planned to return with more spices, per the Synoptic accounts, though the Evangelist does not mention this — the spice quantity of 19:39 may make it unnecessary in his account).</p>'
  },

  "20": {
    "1": '<p>"The first day of the week" (<em>tē mia tōn sabbatōn</em>) is the day after the Jewish Sabbath — what we call Sunday. The Evangelist specifies "early" (<em>prōi</em>) and "while it was still dark" (<em>skotias eti ousēs</em>), which places Mary\'s arrival before dawn. The light/darkness motif has been central to the Fourth Gospel since the prologue (1:4–5, "the light shines in the darkness"); her arrival in the dark mirrors the Nicodemus episode (3:2) and anticipates a movement toward light. Women in Jewish society had primary responsibility for mourning and attending the dead; Mary\'s early visit to the tomb is consistent with this role.</p>',

    "2": '<p>Mary\'s use of "we do not know where they have put him" (plural <em>oidamen</em>) suggests she was not alone, as also implied by the Synoptic accounts (Mark 16:1; Luke 24:10 name several women). The Evangelist focuses on Mary as the central figure but preserves the plural verb, possibly reflecting an independent tradition or the author\'s knowledge of the fuller group. Her report to "the other disciple, the one Jesus loved" alongside Simon Peter pairs the two disciples who will race to the tomb — the Beloved Disciple being defined again by his relationship to Jesus rather than by his name.</p>',

    "3": '<p>The race to the tomb is one of the few passages in the Fourth Gospel that reads like unfiltered eyewitness memory — a specific physical detail (who ran faster, who arrived first, who entered first) that serves no obvious theological purpose and survives without symbolic elaboration. The Evangelist simply records it, which is itself significant: the care taken to distinguish what each disciple saw and did suggests the episode was told and retold in community memory in exactly these terms.</p>',

    "4": '<p>The other disciple outrunning Peter is noted without explanation or theological comment. This has been read as evidence of the Beloved Disciple\'s relative youth (physically faster) or as a social detail (he arrived first, which becomes relevant for the order of entry). Ancient readers would have read the foot-race detail with interest rather than puzzlement — competitive running was a recognized cultural activity, and the observation that one man outran another was perfectly ordinary.</p>',

    "5": '<p>The Greek <em>parakupsas</em> (bent over and looked in) is a physical posture of peering — the same verb is used in 1 Peter 1:12 for the angels longing to look into the gospel mysteries. Tomb entrances in first-century Judea were typically low openings in a rock face, requiring stooping or bending to see inside; the detail is architecturally accurate. The strips of linen lying there but the Beloved Disciple not entering is a carefully observed moment: he sees from outside the threshold, takes in the evidence, but pauses.</p>',

    "6": '<p>Peter\'s characteristic action — entering immediately without hesitation — is consistent with his portrayal throughout the Fourth Gospel (13:37; 18:10; 21:7) as one who acts before reflecting. The strips of linen (<em>othonia</em>) lying there are the same bandaging material used in the burial (19:40); the emptiness inside — cloths present, body absent — is what he sees. The arrangement of what remains becomes the physical puzzle that drives the next verses.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The careful specification of the burial cloth (<em>soudarion</em>) that had been around Jesus\'s head, lying not with the linen strips but "folded up by itself in a separate place," has been argued to distinguish the resurrection from a theft. Grave robbers working quickly would not have unwrapped the body and carefully folded the head cloth; the arrangement implies that the body was not moved but departed from its wrappings. The <em>soudarion</em> was a face-cloth or small linen piece used to bind the jaw during burial or to cover the face of the dead; its distinct placement is a specific detail that would have been immediately visible to Peter as he surveyed the tomb.</p>',

    "8": '<p>The Beloved Disciple enters after Peter, sees the same evidence, and "believed" — with no prior resurrection appearance and apparently no fuller understanding (as v.9 immediately concedes). What he believed is not specified: perhaps belief that the resurrection had occurred, triggered by the evidence that the body had not been taken but had departed differently. The Evangelist\'s sequencing gives the Beloved Disciple priority in faith (he believed first) while giving Peter priority in action (he entered first) — a characterological distinction that runs throughout the Gospel\'s treatment of these two figures.</p>',

    "9": '<p>The Evangelist\'s candid admission that the disciples did not yet understand "the Scripture that he must rise from the dead" is a significant piece of historical self-awareness. Resurrection expectation in Second Temple Judaism was widespread among Pharisees but typically referred to the general resurrection at the end of history, not an individual resurrection in the middle of history before the final judgment. No one in Jesus\'s circle had a framework for interpreting what they were seeing until the resurrection appearances themselves provided one; they had to learn retrospectively what the Scriptures had been pointing toward (cf. 2:22; 12:16 for the same retrospective-understanding pattern).</p>',

    "10": '<p>The return home is narrated without joy or proclamation — the disciples process what they have seen but have not yet encountered the risen Jesus. The Evangelist places this anti-climactic moment deliberately: the empty tomb alone does not produce faith; it produces puzzlement. Mary, who stays behind weeping, will be the first to encounter the risen Christ — the sequence of the narrative emphasizes that the resurrection reveals itself through personal encounter, not just through physical evidence.</p>',

    "11": '<p>Jewish mourning (<em>klaio</em>, wailing/loud weeping) was a public, communal practice — not the private, internalized grief of modern Western culture. Professional mourners were hired for funerals (Matt 9:23 mentions flute players and a noisy crowd); the mourner\'s role was to express grief loudly as an act of honor for the dead. Mary\'s weeping outside the tomb while stooping to look inside is an act of mourning combined with unwillingness to leave — the behavior of someone who cannot yet accept the situation as final. Her position (outside, bending in) mirrors the Beloved Disciple\'s physical posture at v.5, but her emotional state is opposite: he was detached enough to pause and observe; she is absorbed in grief.</p>',

    "12": '<p>The two angels in white seated where Jesus\'s body had been — one at the head, one at the feet — may be the Evangelist\'s deliberate evocation of the mercy seat (<em>kapporet</em>) in the Tabernacle, above which two golden cherubim faced each other with the space between them representing God\'s presence (Exod 25:18–22). If so, the empty space where the body had lain corresponds to the space between the cherubim — the space that is now, paradoxically, the site of God\'s self-disclosure. Angels in white were standard equipment in Second Temple apocalyptic literature for moments of divine revelation (Dan 7; 1 Enoch; the Transfiguration accounts); their presence signals that what has happened is not a human event.</p>',

    "13": '<p>The angels\' question "Woman, why are you crying?" is curious — why would angels ask this if they know the answer? In Jewish angelology and in the Gospels, heavenly messengers sometimes ask questions that function to draw out the human\'s state (cf. Gen 3:9, God\'s "Where are you?" to Adam). Mary\'s response — "They have taken my Lord away and I don\'t know where they have put him" — frames the situation entirely within the category of grave desecration, the most serious transgression against the dead in Jewish law. Her use of "my Lord" (<em>ton Kyrion mou</em>) is an intimate possessive — not a theological title but a personal address — which makes the upcoming recognition scene all the more poignant.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The failure to recognize Jesus immediately upon turning around is a consistent feature of the resurrection appearances across all four Gospels (Luke 24:16, Emmaus; 21:4 here, and implicitly others). Various explanations have been proposed: grief and weeping impairing recognition, the resurrection body having altered characteristics, divine veiling for theological purposes, or simply the unexpectedness of the encounter (the person you saw die is the last person you expect to see walking in a garden). The Evangelist does not explain the non-recognition — he lets it stand as a feature of the encounter that the reader must process alongside Mary.</p>',

    "15": '<p>Thinking the stranger was "the gardener" (<em>ho kēpouros</em>) was reasonable in context: a garden required a caretaker, who would typically be a slave or employee responsible for maintenance and security. Mary\'s request — "if you have carried him away, tell me where you have put him and I will get him" — is both heartbreaking and impractical (a woman alone could not carry a body) but is driven by pure devotion rather than logistics. The garden setting activates resonances with Genesis: Adam was placed in a garden, humanity fell in a garden, and now the one who reverses the fall is encountered in a garden by one who mistakes him for the gardener.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The single utterance of her name — "Mary" — is the turning point of the encounter. The Good Shepherd passage (10:3–4) had described the Shepherd who "calls his own sheep by name" and whose sheep "know his voice"; here that description is enacted. Recognition comes through hearing, not through sight — an epistemological emphasis consistent with the Johannine pattern where belief comes through testimony and encounter rather than through visual proof alone. "Rabboni" is an emphatic Aramaic form of "Rabbi" — the doubled syllable is an affective intensification comparable to the difference between "teacher" and "my dear teacher." It is the word used for God in some Jewish prayers, though Mary uses it in its most personal register.</p>',

    "17": '<p>The prohibition <em>mē mou haptou</em> ("do not hold on to me") has generated extensive interpretation. <em>Haptomai</em> means not just "touch" but "cling to, attach oneself to" — the prohibition is not against physical contact per se (Jesus later invites Thomas to touch, 20:27) but against Mary\'s apparent impulse to restore the previous relationship as if nothing had changed. The reason given — "for I have not yet ascended to the Father" — suggests that the resurrection is not the end of Jesus\'s movement but a transition toward ascension. The instruction "Go instead to my brothers and tell them" is a commission: Mary is sent as an apostle to the apostles. The reclassification of the disciples as "brothers" (<em>adelphous</em>) rather than "servants" (13:16) or "friends" (15:15) marks a new phase of relationship enabled by the glorification event.</p>',

    "18": '<p>Mary Magdalene\'s role as the first Easter witness and the first to announce the resurrection ("I have seen the Lord!") is historically remarkable given that women\'s testimony was legally inadmissible in both Roman courts and (per Josephus) in Jewish judicial proceedings. Josephus writes: "Let no woman be admitted as a witness, on account of the levity and boldness of their sex" (<em>Ant.</em> 4.8.15). If the early church were inventing the resurrection narrative, they would almost certainly not have chosen a woman as the primary witness. The inclusion of Mary Magdalene as the first witness is one of the details that historical critics regard as carrying a high probability of historical authenticity precisely because it is counterproductive to the narrative\'s reception.</p>',

    "19": '<p>The locked doors are emphasized ("the doors being shut," <em>tōn thyrōn kekleismenōn</em>) because they are the obstacle that Jesus\'s arrival defies. The disciples\' fear of "the Jewish leaders" (<em>hoi Ioudaioi</em>) was grounded in the political reality that in Roman law a condemned criminal\'s associates could face charges related to the same offense; the disciples of an executed would-be king of the Jews were legally vulnerable. The peace greeting (<em>Eirēnē hymin</em>, "Peace be to you") is the standard Jewish greeting (<em>shalom alechem</em>), but in context it carries specific weight: the disciples were in fear, and the risen Lord\'s first word to them is peace — the peace he had promised in 14:27 ("Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you").</p>',

    "20": '<p>The showing of the hands and side serves both to identify Jesus (these are the wounds from the crucifixion) and to demonstrate continuity between the crucified and the risen body — the resurrection did not erase the marks of the passion. The disciples\' joy (<em>echārēsan hoi mathētai</em>, "the disciples rejoiced") fulfills the promise of 16:20–22, where Jesus had told them their grief would turn to joy that no one could take from them. The fulfillment of the promise within the same book creates a narrative closure: the reader who remembers the Farewell Discourse is meant to recognize this moment as the promised reversal.</p>',

    "21": '<p>The mission statement "As the Father has sent me, I am sending you" parallels two different verbs in the Greek: <em>apostellō</em> (the Father "sent," from which "apostle" derives) and <em>pempō</em> (Jesus "sends") — the Evangelist uses these interchangeably for divine sending throughout the Gospel. The parallel structure is the foundation of the apostolic commission: the disciples\' authority and mission are derived from, and shaped by, the way the Father sent the Son. Jesus received his mission from the Father with full authority; the disciples receive their mission from Jesus with derived authority. The mission framework presupposed by "as…so" implies similarity of pattern, not identity of status.</p>',

    "22": '<p>The act of breathing on them (<em>enephusēsen</em>) deliberately echoes the Septuagint of Genesis 2:7, where God "breathed into [Adam\'s] nostrils the breath of life" (<em>enephusēsen eis to prosōpon autou pnoēn zōēs</em>). The LXX uses the same rare compound verb (<em>emphusaō</em>) in both places — the Evangelist signals new creation by repeating the creative act of the first creation. This is the Fourth Gospel\'s account of Pentecost: what Acts 2 narrates as a corporate event with wind and fire, the Evangelist narrates as an intimate, private moment of direct breath. Whether the two accounts describe the same event (theologically) or different stages is a longstanding question; both present the gift of the Spirit as the transforming power behind the apostolic mission.</p>',

    "23": '<p>The authority to forgive or retain sins corresponds to the rabbinic and early Christian practice of community discipline. In Second Temple Judaism, the community at Qumran and the Pharisaic <em>ḥavurot</em> (fellowships) both exercised forms of exclusion and reinstatement that functioned as the retaining and releasing of sins within a defined community. The parallel in Matthew 16:19 and 18:18 uses the language of "binding and loosing" — technical terms in rabbinic law for declaring something permitted or forbidden, and for excommunicating or reinstating a community member. The early church understood this authority as applying to communal discipline and the liturgical pronouncement of absolution, not as granting individuals the power to determine cosmic destinies.</p>',

    "24": '<p>Thomas\'s absence from the first resurrection appearance places him in exactly the situation of subsequent generations: he has not seen; he has only heard the testimony of others who have. His subsequent demand for physical evidence ("unless I see the nail marks and put my finger where the nails were") is usually read as blameworthy skepticism, but it is worth noting that Thomas is asking for exactly the kind of evidence that Peter and the Beloved Disciple had just examined at the empty tomb — direct physical inspection. He is not refusing faith in principle; he is refusing to accept secondhand testimony as a substitute for firsthand evidence. The beatitude of v.29 ("blessed are those who have not seen and yet have believed") is the Evangelist\'s response to this position, addressed to the reader.</p>',

    "25": '<p>Thomas\'s specification of "the nail marks" and "his side" identifies the specific wounds from the crucifixion as the evidence he requires. Roman crucifixion typically involved nails driven through the wrists (or hands/lower forearm, where the bone structure could support the body\'s weight) and through the feet; the spear wound to the side was confirmed in the Evangelist\'s account (19:34). Thomas\'s demand is for the same evidence the soldiers had already examined at the cross (19:32–34) — physical inspection of the crucified body. The fact that these wounds persist in the resurrection body is theologically significant: the resurrection affirms the crucifixion rather than erasing it.</p>',

    "26": '<p>"After eight days" (<em>meth\' hēmeras oktō</em>) in the Jewish reckoning means a week later on the same day of the week — both the day of departure and the day of return are counted, so "eight days" from Sunday to the following Sunday. The pattern of Sunday appearances became the basis for the early Christian practice of assembling on the first day of the week (Acts 20:7; 1 Cor 16:2), distinguishing Christian worship from Jewish Sabbath observance. The second appearance follows the same pattern as the first (locked doors, "Peace be with you") but is specifically arranged for Thomas\'s benefit — the sequence of appearances is not random but responsive to the community\'s needs.</p>',

    "27": '<p>Jesus\'s invitation to Thomas — "Put your finger here; see my hands. Reach out your hand and put it into my side" — issues exactly the terms of evidence Thomas had demanded in v.25. Whether Thomas actually touches the wounds is left open by the Evangelist; the next verse jumps immediately to Thomas\'s confession without narrating physical contact. The invitation itself may have been sufficient: being addressed directly by the risen Jesus and invited to examine the wounds may have produced faith before the examination was completed. The key phrase "stop being unbelieving but believing" (<em>mē ginou apistos alla pistos</em>) is a present imperative with the implication of ongoing disposition — not merely a single act of belief but a settled orientation.</p>',

    "28": '<p>Thomas\'s confession "My Lord and my God!" (<em>ho Kyrios mou kai ho Theos mou</em>) is the climactic Christological statement of the Gospel, echoing and answering the prologue\'s "the Word was God" (1:1). The double title — Lord (<em>Kyrios</em>) and God (<em>Theos</em>) with the emphatic possessive <em>mou</em> (my) twice — is unparalleled in Jewish address to a human being. In Roman imperial culture, the title <em>dominus et deus</em> (lord and god) was used of the emperor Domitian (Suetonius, <em>Domitian</em> 13.2; Pliny, <em>Pan.</em> 2.3); if the Fourth Gospel was composed in the period of Domitian\'s reign (late first century), the confession reads as a counter-imperial declaration: Thomas applies to Jesus the title claimed by the emperor. The confession also recalls Psalm 35:23 (LXX 34:23): "Awake and rise to my defense! Contend for me, my God and Lord" — a Psalm of the suffering righteous person vindicated by God.</p>',

    "29": '<p>The beatitude "Blessed are those who have not seen and yet have believed" addresses the situation of the Evangelist\'s community and of every subsequent reader. The Fourth Gospel was written after the generation of eyewitnesses had passed or was passing; the community it addresses could not see Jesus as Thomas did. The beatitude does not disparage sight-based faith (the whole Gospel is built on the testimony of witnesses who did see); it affirms that faith transmitted through testimony is sufficient, and those who believe on such testimony are <em>not</em> at a disadvantage compared to eyewitnesses. The Evangelist\'s stated purpose in vv.30–31 confirms this: the book exists precisely so that people who were not present can come to faith.</p>',

    "30": '<p>The reference to "many other signs" not recorded in the Gospel (<em>polla alla sēmeia</em>) acknowledges that the text is a selection, not a comprehensive record. The word <em>sēmeia</em> (signs) has been the Fourth Gospel\'s primary category for Jesus\'s miracles throughout (the seven signs: water-to-wine, healing the official\'s son, healing the paralytic, feeding the five thousand, walking on water, healing the blind man, raising Lazarus). The selection from the available material is explicitly purposive — the Evangelist chose particular signs for a particular effect on a particular audience. Ancient readers would have recognized this as a standard authorial statement about the scope of a work.</p>',

    "31": '<p>The statement of purpose — "these are written so that you may believe that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God, and that by believing you may have life in his name" — is the Gospel\'s formal thesis statement, placed at its structural conclusion (before the appendix). The textual variant between <em>pisteuēte</em> (aorist, "come to believe") and <em>pisteuēte</em> (present, "continue believing") affects whether the Gospel is understood as primarily evangelistic (aimed at initial conversion) or catechetical (aimed at deepening existing faith); the manuscript evidence is divided, and both purposes likely coexist. The two titles — "the Messiah" and "the Son of God" — are the two halves of the Johannine confession: the Jewish messianic expectation (the anointed king from David\'s line) and the divine identity claim (the unique Son who shares the Father\'s nature). Both are required; neither alone is sufficient.</p>'
  },

  "21": {
    "1": '<p>The Sea of Tiberias was the Roman name for the Sea of Galilee — Herod Antipas renamed it after Emperor Tiberius when he founded the city of Tiberias on its western shore (ca. 20 CE). The Jewish name "Sea of Galilee" (<em>Yam Kinneret</em>) was the older designation; the Roman name appears in official and Hellenized contexts. The Evangelist\'s use of the Roman name (also at 6:1) may reflect the cosmopolitan milieu of his audience or simply the common usage of his region. This epilogue (chapter 21) is widely recognized as an addition to the Gospel\'s original form: chapter 20:30–31 reads as a natural conclusion, and chapter 21 opens with a resumptive "afterward" — but the chapter\'s content and vocabulary are consistent with Johannine authorship.</p>',

    "2": '<p>The list of disciples present includes figures who do not appear prominently in the main body of the Fourth Gospel: "the sons of Zebedee" are not named in the Gospel proper (unlike the Synoptics, which name James and John throughout); "two other disciples" are entirely anonymous. The naming of Thomas and Nathanael alongside Simon Peter signals a Galilean gathering — these are the disciples whose stories are told, and the Evangelist positions them together as a community group rather than scattered individuals. The phrase "two other disciples" has led to the long tradition of identifying one of them as the Beloved Disciple, who has been anonymous throughout.</p>',

    "3": '<p>Night fishing on the Sea of Galilee was the standard commercial method. Fish schooled in deeper water during the day; at night they rose toward the surface and shallower water where nets could reach them. The large dragnets used on the sea required multiple hands and were typically worked from boats in the hours of darkness. Peter\'s "I\'m going out to fish" (<em>hypagō halieuein</em>) reads in context as either a practical decision (he had to do something; sitting and waiting was unbearable) or a regression toward his pre-call life. The night-long effort with nothing caught mirrors Luke 5:5 ("we\'ve worked hard all night and haven\'t caught anything"), which precedes a different miraculous catch — the Evangelist\'s epilogue is in deliberate dialogue with that earlier scene.</p>',

    "4": '<p>Dawn (<em>prōias de ēdē ginomenēs</em>, "morning already coming") was the end of the night-fishing period and the moment when catches were tallied and nets brought in. The disciples\' failure to recognize Jesus on the shore echoes Mary\'s failure in 20:14 — the resurrection appearances in the Fourth Gospel are characterized by an initial non-recognition that requires a specific revelatory moment to overcome. The shore would be roughly 100 yards away (cf. v.8, "about two hundred cubits"), close enough to hear and see but far enough for features to be indistinct in the early morning light.</p>',

    "5": '<p>The address <em>paidia</em> ("children," "friends," "lads") is a colloquial vocative used between close acquaintances — less formal than <em>teknia</em> (little children, the address Jesus uses in 13:33) and more like the way a senior would address juniors with affectionate familiarity. The question "You don\'t have any fish, do you?" uses a construction that expects the answer "no" — it is not exactly a question; it is a gently teasing observation. The disciples\' single-word answer <em>ou</em> (no) captures the exhaustion and brevity of men who have nothing to show for a night\'s work.</p>',

    "6": '<p>The instruction to cast the net on "the right side of the boat" is specific in its directionality. In Greco-Roman culture the right side was the favorable side — the Latin <em>sinister</em> (left) conveyed ill omen while <em>dexter</em> (right) was auspicious. Whether the Evangelist intends a symbolic reading or is preserving a specific instruction from the account is unclear. The instantaneous result — so many fish they could not haul the net in — is the reversal of a full night of failure in a single cast. The Luke 5 parallel features the same dramatic reversal in the same setting; the Evangelist\'s version reserves the full symbolism of the catch for the restoration scene that follows.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The Beloved Disciple recognizes Jesus first ("It is the Lord!") before Peter does — the same priority he had at the empty tomb (20:8). Peter\'s response is characteristically physical and immediate: he puts on his outer garment (<em>ton ependytēn</em>) before jumping into the water. The behavior is counterintuitive (one strips to swim) but reflects an honor code: to approach a superior undressed, especially a divine or royal figure, was a gesture of disrespect. Putting on his garment before leaping expresses the same instinct as the angels\'s coverings before the divine presence — Peter is both impulsive (he cannot wait for the boat) and respectful (he will not approach the Lord unclothed).</p>',

    "8": '<p>The Evangelist\'s measurement of the boat\'s distance from shore — "about a hundred yards" (<em>apo pēchōn diakosīōn</em>, two hundred cubits, roughly 300 feet or 100 meters) — is the kind of specific, practical detail that appears throughout the Gospel in ways that suggest eyewitness memory: the six jars each holding 20–30 gallons (2:6), the 38 years of illness (5:5), Lazarus four days in the tomb (11:17), the 300 denarii ointment (12:5). Whether these numbers derive from direct memory, oral tradition, or source material, they give the narrative a texture different from symbolic or invented numbers.</p>',

    "9": '<p>The "fire of coals" (<em>anthrakia</em>) is the detail the Evangelist wants the reader to notice: the Greek word <em>anthrakia</em> appears only twice in the New Testament, and both occurrences are in the Fourth Gospel — here (21:9) and at 18:18, where Peter stood warming himself at a charcoal fire while denying Jesus three times. The verbal repetition is the Evangelist\'s signal that the setting of the restoration scene is a deliberate echo of the setting of the betrayal. The Beloved Disciple recognized Jesus from a distance; Peter is drawn to a fire that is the same kind of fire at which he failed. The stage is being set for the threefold restoration that will mirror the threefold denial.</p>',

    "10": '<p>Jesus\'s invitation to "bring some of the fish you have just caught" — before the meal he has prepared — is an act of inclusion: their catch, miraculous as it is, is incorporated into the shared meal. The pattern of Jesus receiving human effort and incorporating it into divine provision runs throughout the Gospel (the five loaves the boy brings in ch.6 are incorporated into the feeding; the water the servants draw is incorporated into the wine-making). The disciples are not passive recipients of Jesus\'s provision but participants who bring what they have.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The number 153 has attracted more interpretive speculation than almost any other numerical detail in the Fourth Gospel. Jerome (4th century) cited the ancient natural history tradition (found in Oppian\'s <em>Halieutica</em>) that exactly 153 species of fish existed in the known world, reading the catch as a symbol of the universal scope of the apostolic mission. Augustine proposed a mathematical reading: 153 is a "triangular number" (1+2+3+...+17=153), and 17 = 10 (commandments) + 7 (gifts of the Spirit). Others have proposed gematria connections. The most sober observation is that the Evangelist names the specific number without interpreting it — which may simply mean the number was part of the story as told and retold, preserved because it was exact and memorable. The unbroken net, unlike the broken net in Luke 5:6, signals the capacity of the mission to hold all who are gathered.</p>',

    "12": '<p>The meal on the beach — Jesus distributing bread and fish — echoes the language of 6:11 ("Jesus then took the loaves, gave thanks, and distributed to those who were seated, as much as they wanted; he did the same with the fish") so closely that early Christian readers would have heard it as a Eucharistic resonance. "Come and have breakfast" (<em>deute aristēsate</em>) is an act of hospitality: the host provides, the guests come. The peculiar note "none of the disciples dared ask him \'Who are you?\' They knew it was the Lord" captures the strange quality of these resurrection appearances — there is certainty of identity combined with an inability to interrogate it, as if the disciples recognize that asking is unnecessary and somehow improper.</p>',

    "13": '<p>Jesus\'s action of taking the bread and giving it to them, and doing the same with the fish, is formally described with the same eucharistic pattern found in the feeding narratives (6:11) and in Luke\'s Emmaus account (Luke 24:30: "he took bread, gave thanks, broke it and began to give it to them"). The meals of the risen Jesus in the resurrection narratives served a dual function for the early church: they demonstrated that the resurrection body was genuinely physical (against purely spiritual interpretations) and they provided the pattern for the eucharistic gatherings through which the risen Lord continued to be present. This beach breakfast was remembered as a third appearance (v.14), distinct and countable.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The Evangelist\'s numbering of the post-resurrection appearances — "this was now the third time Jesus appeared to his disciples after he was raised from the dead" — reflects a count of group appearances to the disciples: 20:19, 20:26, and now 21:1–14. Mary Magdalene\'s individual encounter (20:14–18) is not counted in this sequence, which numbers the appearances to the community of disciples rather than all appearances. The numbering gesture conveys a sense of narrative ordering and closure: the appearances are not random or infinite; they follow a pattern and are being counted and remembered.</p>',

    "15": '<p>The meal concluded, Jesus addresses Peter using his formal name "Simon son of John" — the same form used when Jesus first named him (1:42: "You will be called Cephas"). The reversion to the birth name rather than the given name "Peter" may signal a return to the original call: the relationship is being reconstituted from its foundation. The question "Do you love me more than these?" (<em>agapas me pleon toutōn</em>) most naturally refers to the other disciples: Peter had declared "I will lay down my life for you" (13:37) and positioned himself as uniquely loyal; the question probes whether that claim survived the denial. Peter\'s response — using <em>philō</em> where Jesus asked with <em>agapas</em> — has generated extensive debate about whether the Evangelist intends a distinction between <em>agapē</em> (selfless love) and <em>philia</em> (personal affection); the commission "Feed my lambs" (<em>boske ta arnia mou</em>) follows regardless of how the love question resolves.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The second exchange drops the comparative "more than these" and focuses on Peter alone: "do you love me?" The Evangelist varies the verbs for "feed" and "shepherd" (<em>boske</em> / <em>poimaine</em>) and the words for the flock (<em>arnia</em> / <em>probata</em>: lambs / sheep) across the three exchanges, creating a pattern that is neither perfectly parallel nor arbitrarily varied. <em>Poimaine</em> (shepherd) implies a broader role — guiding, protecting, leading — while <em>boske</em> (feed) focuses on provision. The alternation may indicate different aspects of pastoral responsibility, or it may simply reflect the Evangelist\'s stylistic preference for variation within repetition, visible throughout the Gospel (cf. the alternation of <em>pempō</em> and <em>apostellō</em> for divine sending).</p>',

    "17": '<p>On the third question, Jesus shifts to Peter\'s word — "do you <em>phileis</em> me?" — and Peter is hurt precisely because the change of word implies Jesus is now questioning even the lesser claim. The threefold structure mirrors the threefold denial at the charcoal fire (18:15–18, 25–27): three questions at a charcoal fire answer three denials at a charcoal fire. The restoration is structurally complete. Peter\'s final response adds the appeal to Jesus\'s omniscience — "Lord, you know all things; you know that I love you" — the same appeal he implicitly made in 13:37 ("I will lay down my life for you") but now without bravado, and now with the understanding that Jesus knows the truth of the claim better than Peter does. The pastoral commission "Feed my sheep" is given three times regardless of Peter\'s uncertainty — the commission is not contingent on Peter\'s self-confidence but on Jesus\'s re-calling.</p>',

    "18": '<p>The prophecy of Peter\'s death uses an idiom that was recognizable in early Christian circles as a reference to crucifixion. "You will stretch out your hands and someone else will dress you and lead you where you do not want to go" — "stretching out the hands" (<em>ekteneis tas cheiras sou</em>) was used in early Christian literature to describe crucifixion specifically (Barnabas 12:4; Justin, <em>Apology</em> 1.35). The contrast with youthful independence ("when you were young, you dressed yourself and went where you wanted") follows the ancient topos of youth as vigorous and self-directed, old age as dependent — but the Evangelist inverts it: old age for Peter will involve not natural infirmity but imposed constraint in service of his witness. Historical tradition places Peter\'s martyrdom by crucifixion in Rome under Nero (ca. 64–68 CE) — 1 Clement 5:4 and Ignatius\'s letter to the Romans (4:3) both presuppose his death there.</p>',

    "19": '<p>The Evangelist\'s explanatory note — "Jesus said this to indicate the kind of death by which Peter would glorify God" — is unusually explicit: he tells the reader the interpretive key to the prophecy rather than leaving it implicit. The phrase "glorify God" in death (<em>doxasei ton Theon</em>) uses the language of the Johannine Passion: Jesus\'s death was his glorification (13:31; 17:1). Peter\'s coming death is placed in the same category — his martyrdom will be his participation in the pattern of glorification through faithful suffering. The command "Follow me" closes the circle: it is the same imperative with which Jesus called his first disciples (1:43, "Follow me" to Philip; implied in 1:40–42 for Peter and Andrew). The Gospel ends where it began: the same call, now with the full weight of its cost known.</p>',

    "20": '<p>Peter\'s question about the Beloved Disciple — asked immediately after receiving his own death-prophecy — is a very human response: "what about him?" (<em>houtos de ti</em>). The Beloved Disciple is described as "following" (<em>akolouthountos</em>) — the same word used for discipleship throughout the Gospel. Whether this "following" is physical (he is literally walking behind them in this scene) or narrative (he is the one who follows in the literary sense) is ambiguous; both readings work. The parenthetical identification — "This was the one who had leaned back against Jesus at the supper and had said, \'Lord, who is going to betray you?\'" — anchors the Beloved Disciple\'s identity in the specific narrative moment of 13:23–25, the most intimate scene in the Last Supper.</p>',

    "21": '<p>Peter\'s question about the Beloved Disciple\'s fate — "Lord, what about him?" — invites a comparison of destinies, which Jesus declines to provide. The exchange suggests that in the Evangelist\'s community, the comparative status or fate of the Beloved Disciple was a live question, perhaps a source of rivalry or anxiety. The deflection "If I want him to remain alive until I return, what is that to you? You must follow me" is a lesson in the proper scope of a disciple\'s concern: each person\'s calling is their own, not a comparison point against another\'s. The response also implicitly acknowledges different vocations — Peter\'s martyrdom and the Beloved Disciple\'s different trajectory — without adjudicating which was greater.</p>',

    "22": '<p>The conditional statement "If I want him to remain until I return" (<em>ean auton thelō menein heōs erchomai</em>) became a rumor that the Beloved Disciple would not die — a misreading of a conditional as a promise. The Evangelist\'s correction of this rumor in v.23 suggests that by the time of writing, the Beloved Disciple had died (or was near death), creating a theological problem for the community: if he was supposed to live until the return of Christ, why had he died? The Evangelist\'s response is exegetical — Jesus did not say "he will not die" but "If I want him to remain, what is that to you?" The correction is also a hermeneutical lesson about reading conditional statements as unconditional promises.</p>',

    "23": '<p>The spread of the rumor "among the believers" (<em>en tois adelphois</em>, "among the brothers") that the Beloved Disciple would not die shows how oral tradition could misfire in transmission — a qualified statement became an unqualified promise through the normal processes of retelling. The Evangelist\'s precise quotation of what Jesus actually said ("If I want him to remain...") versus what was misremembered ("that disciple would not die") is itself a demonstration of the value of written testimony over oral tradition — the written Gospel preserves the exact conditional structure that oral tradition had flattened into an assertion. This may be one reason the community endorsed committing the Evangelist\'s testimony to written form (v.24).</p>',

    "24": '<p>The switch to "we" — "We know that his testimony is true" — is a seam visible in the text: the "we" vouches for the Beloved Disciple\'s testimony, suggesting that a community or group of editors authenticated the Gospel before its circulation. The claim that "this is the disciple who testifies to these things and who wrote them down" does not necessarily mean the Beloved Disciple personally inscribed every word; ancient authorship could encompass dictating to a scribe, providing the oral testimony that a redactor shaped into text, or serving as the authorizing source. The Johannine school or community that stands behind the "we" presents itself as the collective guarantor of the tradition\'s integrity — a function analogous to the court witness or legal oath of attestation.</p>',

    "25": '<p>The closing hyperbole — "if every one of them were written down, I suppose that even the whole world would not have room for the books that would be written" — is a recognized rhetorical device (<em>hyperbole</em>) used in Jewish and Greco-Roman literature to convey incomprehensible vastness. Philo uses similar language; Ecclesiastes 12:12 laments the endless making of books. The Evangelist closes with a gesture toward the inexhaustible significance of Jesus: the selection that has been made (20:30–31 explained the principle of selection) is a finite book about an infinite subject. It is a characteristically Johannine ending — the Gospel that began before time ("In the beginning was the Word") ends by gesturing beyond what could be contained in all the books the world could hold.</p>'
  }
}


